{
  "text": "Each of the three simulations requires individualized boundary conditions for its specification. For the first simulation, two flowrates at the superficial femoral artery were investigated, 1900 and 190 ml/min, respectively. These values correspond to the maximum and time-averaged flowrates for diseased superficial femoral arteries [CITATION_1] . Along the path of flow, a number of branches is encountered and at the exit of each branch, a gauge pressure of zero was specified. At the downstream end of the system, information was available for the respective velocities at the locations II, III, and IV from experiments carried out on diseased individuals [CITATION_2] Fig. (5b) . These values are 11.4, 13.3, and 11.4 cm/s respectively for the maximum overall flowrate. At the lower overall flowrate, the corresponding values are 4.3, 7.4, and 4.3 cm/s. For the second of the modeled lesions, the flowrates boundary conditions at the inlet (popliteal artery) were 920 ml/min and 89.9 ml/min. The velocities at the locations II-IV were maintained as before. The third modeled lesion was characterized by inlet flowrates of 220 and 32 ml/min and by exit velocities as in the foregoing discussion. All of the above referenced blood flow information was taken from the literature [CITATION_3] . For the second simulation, which corresponded to a lesion located in the Popliteal Artery, the inlet flowrate was taken from the simulations which were previously completed for lesions at the Superficial Femoral Artery. The number of elements that was used in the final simulation runs exceeded seven million. That number of elements was determined on the basis of a mesh-independence study in which the metric used for comparison was the flowrates at the branching arteries in the system.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "2810510",
    "[CITATION_2]": "2810510",
    "[CITATION_3]": "2810510"
